The entire inland state of Bolivia still remembers the coastline they lost to Chile during a bloody resource conflict in the 1800's, and the country longs to once again sail the Pacific.
These hopes are perhaps greater than they have been for decades, with Bolivia awaiting a ruling from the International Court of Justice on 1 October after five years of deliberations.
"Bolivia has drive, community spirit and calm, and of course it is waiting for the result with a positive attitude", said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will see the ruling from the International Court of Justice on large screens at many different locations in the country, in the hope that the Court in The Hague will give its ruling in favor of Bolivia's claim that Chile  after several decades of sporadic negotiations  is obliged to negotiate to give Bolivia its own outlet to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia's charismatic native-born president who faces a controversial re-election campaign next year, has also invested heavily in Monday's sentiment.
"We are very close to a return to the Pacific", he promised late in August.
But some analysts believe that the court will hardly take Bolivia's side, and that very little would change if it had done so.
The UN body, which is based in the Netherlands, has no authority to give away Chilean land areas, and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of any negotiations.
The fact that the ruling from the International Court of Justice came only six months after the last arguments were heard suggests that the case was not complicated, according to Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert on international law.
And rather than promoting Bolivia's cause, the last four years may have actually made things worse.
The problem of access to the sea has been captured by the current Bolivian administration, said Zárate.
She believes Morales' antagonistic rhetoric has teared away all eventual remaining goodwill on Chile's side.
Bolivia and Chile will continue negotiations on one or another point, but it will be extremely difficult to discuss the matter after this.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former president Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia's representative at The Hague, rejected the theory that the court's decision came unusually quickly.
According to him, Monday will give Bolivia an extraordinary opportunity to open a new generation of relations with Chile and the opportunity to put a stop to 139 years of disagreement, to the benefit of both parties.
Calzadilla also denied that Morales, who is still one of Latin America's most popular presidents, has used the maritime situation as a political scaffolding.
"Bolivia will never give up its right to access the Pacific", he added.
