North Korea will not agree to unilateral disarmament without confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions strengthened mistrust of the United States, and that the country would not agree to unilaterally release its nuclear weapons under such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the World Health Organization's annual general assembly that North Korea has taken significant well-intentioned steps over the past year, including halting atomic and missile tests, dismantling the atomic test site and promising not to spread nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"We have not seen any similar response from the United States", he said.
"Without trust in the United States, we have no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances, we will not under any circumstances unilaterally disarm ourselves first".
Ri repeated well-known North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to gradual nuclear disarmament, with North Korea being rewarded for gradual disarmament, but his declaration was significant because it did not reject unilateral nuclear disarmament completely, as Pyongyang has done previously.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump issued in Singapore on June 12, at the very first meeting between a sitting president of the United States and a North Korean leader, in which Kim promised to work toward atomnedrusting of the Korean peninsula, while Trump guaranteed North Korea's security.
North Korea has called for a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first release its atomic weapons.
Washington has also opposed calls to reduce strict international sanctions against North Korea.
The US insists on atomic disarmament first, and raises pressure via sanctions to achieve its goal with force, and opposes itself to even the 'declaration of war's end', according to Ri.
The belief that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a dream for people who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions create further mistrust.
Ri did not mention the plans for a second meeting between Kim and Trump, which the US leader stressed before the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae during the last five months, adding: "If the other party in this disarmament issue were South Korea, rather than the United States, the nuclear disarmament of the Korean Peninsula would not have been as tightly locked as it is".
The tone of Rice's speech was however very different from last year's, when he told the UN General Assembly that an attack on the mainland-USA with North Korea's rockets was inevitable after Trump called Kim a "rocket man" on a suicide mission.
After threatening to "completely destroy" North Korea last year, Trump stood before the United Nations this year and praised Kim for being brave enough to take the arms reduction step, but said much work still remains, and sanctions must remain in place until North Korea is atomically disarmed.
On Wednesday, Trump saw that he didn't have a time frame for this, and said that "It doesn't matter if it takes two years, three years or five months".
China and Russia believe the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures it has taken.
But US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday that "the Security Council's sanctions must still be enforced forcefully and without exception until we have achieved complete, final and confirmed nuclear disarmament".
The Security Council has unanimously increased sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to curb the financing of Pyongyang's atomic and missile weapons programs.
