Students at Harvard are taking a course in getting enough rest.
A new course at Harvard University this year will help students get more sleep by tackling the growing culture of puffing through the night with caffeine as fuel.
One academic found that students at the world's best universities often had no idea how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, developed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He started the course after he gave a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
After I finished, a girl came to me and said, "Why didn't anyone tell me this before?"
She said that no one had ever told her how important sleep was, and that surprised me", he told The Telegraph.
The course, which starts this year, explains to students how important it is to have good sleep habits for academic and athletic performance, and for the general public.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and director of the university's health services, said that the university decided to start the course after they saw that students were suffering from severe sleep deprivation.
The course, which lasts one hour, has a series of interactive tasks.
In one part, there's a picture of a room in a dormitory where students can click on coffee cups, curtains, jogging shoes and books and hear about the effects of caffeine and light and how sports performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and how important it is to have a sleep routine.
In another part, participants learn how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus with interactive icons gets participants to think about their own daily routine.
We realize that this isn't going to change student behavior immediately.
But we think they have a right to know about this, just as you have a right to know about the risks of smoking", said Professor Czeisler.
There is still a certain pride in being able to pug all night, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students led to sleep deprivation being an increasing problem.
He said that enough and good sleep should be the students' "secret weapon" against stress, fatigue and anxiety, and even as a means against weight gain, because lack of sleep puts the brain in a hunger mode, which leads to a constant feeling of hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California chemistry and physical biology student, helped Professor Czeisler to develop the course, taking one of the professor's classes last year, his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course inspired him to work on a course that was available to the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all master's students to take a similar programme before they are enrolled at the university.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set alarms for when to go to bed and when to get up, and that they be aware of the harmful effects of blue light from electronic displays and LED lights, which can disrupt the circadian rhythm and lead to sleep problems.
