New cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to see cancer cells
New cancer vaccine can teach the immune system to see cancer cells and kill them
The vaccine teaches the immune system to recognize cancer cells as part of the treatment
The method involves taking immune cells from a patient and changing them in a laboratory.
The cells can now see a protein that is common in many cancers, and then inject it back into the patient.
A vaccine under trial has shown promising results among patients with different types of cancer.
One woman who received the vaccine, which teaches the immune system to recognize cancer cells, experienced that the ovarian cancer she suffered from disappeared for over 18 months.
The method involves taking immune cells from a patient, changing them in the laboratory so that they can see a protein called HER2, which is typical of many cancers, and then injecting those cells back into the patient.
