Algae bloom updates: Concentrations are reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from Florida's Commission on Fisheries and Wildlife (FWC) shows a general decline in red algae concentrations for parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to FWC, there are reports of fleck-like blooms in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier County, which suggests reduced concentrations.
A blossoming of red algae stretches about 210 km along the coast, from north in Pinellas to south in Lee County.
There are spots around 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but fewer places than in the previous week.
Red algae have also been observed in Pasco County.
There have been reports of moderately large concentrations at or off the coast of Pinellas County in the past week, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, natural to high concentrations in Manatee County, natural to high concentrations at or off the coast of Sarasota County, natural to medium concentrations in Charlotte County, natural to high concentrations at or off the coast of Lee County and low concentrations in Collier County.
There is still a report of irritation in the airways of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier County.
No irritation was reported in the airways northwest of Florida during the past week.
